22:39.992 --> 22:45.631 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to the
national security
and diplomatic transition from
the Obama to

22:45.731 --> 22:47.700 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the Trump administrations.

22:47.800 --> 22:53.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Last week, I asked outgoing
Secretary of State
John Kerry how well the
transition was proceeding.

22:53.772 --> 22:58.344 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And he bluntly answered,
"Smoothly, because
there's not an enormous amount
of it."

22:58.444 --> 23:02.982 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He also said he had yet to meet
his designated
successor, Rex Tillerson.

23:03.082 --> 23:08.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today, with less than 24 hours
left in his
tenure, Kerry's spokesman was
asked if the

23:08.454 --> 23:10.222 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
two men had met.

23:10.322 --> 23:12.825 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN KIRBY, Pentagon Press
Secretary: The
secretary made very clear that
he was willing

23:12.925 --> 23:16.729 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to met with Mr. Tillerson.

23:16.829 --> 23:21.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, as I understand it, they
just weren't
able to get it on the schedule.

23:21.500 --> 23:24.336 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So -- but he did speak to him on
the phone.

23:24.436 --> 23:30.342 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think it was trying to work
both men's schedules.

23:30.442 --> 23:34.146 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As you know, the secretary also
went on a
weeklong trip.

23:34.246 --> 23:38.584 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, he -- they worked to try to
make it happen.

23:38.684 --> 23:44.223 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they just weren't able to
get it on both
men's schedule at a time that
was mutually

23:44.323 --> 23:46.191 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
convenient for both of them.

23:46.292 --> 23:50.296 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Apart from Kerry
and Tillerson,
some Obama Cabinet secretaries
have met their

23:50.396 --> 23:52.231 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
designated successors.

23:52.331 --> 23:57.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, as John Yang reported
earlier, the incoming
Trump administration was forced
to defend

23:57.536 --> 24:03.275 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the pace of its staffing of
important national
security and diplomatic jobs
today after a

24:03.375 --> 24:07.646 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
series of reports detailed a
disjointed transition.

24:07.746 --> 24:11.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For that, we turn now to the
author of one
of those reports, New York Times
White House

24:11.550 --> 24:15.387 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
correspondent Mark Landler, and
to Roger Cressey.

24:15.487 --> 24:21.327 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He was the deputy for
counterterrorism on
the National Security Council
staff from 1999

24:21.427 --> 24:22.961 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to 2001.

24:23.062 --> 24:27.299 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
He was there during the
transition from President
Clinton to George W. Bush.

24:27.399 --> 24:30.169 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He is now a security consultant.

24:30.269 --> 24:32.504 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we welcome both of you to
the "NewsHour."

24:32.604 --> 24:34.506 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Mark Landler, to you first.

24:34.606 --> 24:39.511 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In that story you wrote
yesterday, you referred
to the staff of president-elect
Trump barely

24:39.611 --> 24:46.218 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
having engaged with the current
National Security
Council staff below the most
senior levels.

24:46.318 --> 24:48.721 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What is the level of contact
between the two?

24:48.821 --> 24:52.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK LANDLER, The New York
Times: Well, the
incoming national security
adviser, General

24:52.958 --> 24:58.330 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Michael Flynn, has met four
times with his
predecessor, Susan Rice.

24:58.430 --> 25:02.634 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there has been significant
meetings at
the deputy level, K.T.

25:02.735 --> 25:08.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
McFarland with Admiral Haines,
and at one
level below that, General Keith
Kellogg, who

25:08.607 --> 25:11.710 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is going to be the incoming
chief of staff
of the NSC.

25:11.810 --> 25:16.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But below that level, which is
to say, all
the senior directors that
oversee departments

25:16.915 --> 25:22.855 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
in the National Security
Council, there has
been very little, if any
contact.

25:22.955 --> 25:27.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this is for a number of
reasons, one of
which is the fact that the Trump
transition

25:27.292 --> 25:31.363 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
has been marked by a kind of a
rotating cast.

25:31.463 --> 25:37.236 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The NSC and the White House is
now dealing
with the third transition team
since the election.

25:37.336 --> 25:42.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And with that constant upheaval,
it's been
difficult for them to establish
relationships,

25:43.008 --> 25:48.147 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for the Trump people to get the
security clearances
they need to begin reading
classified information.

25:48.247 --> 25:54.420 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, a process that would have
unfolded pretty
intensively starting on November
10 or 11

25:54.520 --> 25:58.157 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has really only swung into gear
really in
the last two weeks.

25:58.257 --> 26:01.193 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Roger Cressey,
what are you
hearing about how it's going to
at the National

26:01.293 --> 26:03.162 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Security Council?

26:03.262 --> 26:05.197 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROGER CRESSEY, Former National
Security County
Staff: Well, they have
definitely lost time.

26:05.297 --> 26:09.201 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And I think there is some
concern on the part
of the career people that there
is not enough

26:09.301 --> 26:14.506 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
communication with the incoming
team, so that
the new team is fully up on all
the nuances

26:14.606 --> 26:16.308 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of what they're inheriting.

26:16.408 --> 26:19.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The reality, Judy, is, no matter
who comes
into office, they're always
unprepared for

26:20.012 --> 26:21.814 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
what they're about to inherit.

26:21.914 --> 26:25.884 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And I think there is some
concern that there
may not be enough preparation
before the new

26:25.984 --> 26:27.719 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
team arrives tomorrow.

26:27.820 --> 26:31.890 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Roger
Cressey, staying
with you, how does this compare
to previous

26:31.990 --> 26:33.459 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
transitions?

26:33.559 --> 26:35.327 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROGER CRESSEY: Well, we have
seen some where
they have been very short.

26:35.427 --> 26:41.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When I was there in 2000-2001
with -- going
from President Clinton to
President Bush,

26:41.433 --> 26:43.202 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that was very short.

26:43.302 --> 26:48.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, even then, we met with
Condi Rice, with
Steve Hadley, the national
security adviser,

26:48.607 --> 26:50.476 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the deputy.

26:50.576 --> 26:53.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They went around to each office
to meet the
team that was there that they
were inheriting

26:53.412 --> 26:56.381 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
and also to get a better
perspective on what
each office was doing.

26:56.482 --> 26:59.284 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think the challenge for
General Flynn,
for K.T.

26:59.384 --> 27:04.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
McFarland is to get up to speed
as quickly
as possible with the career
people that are

27:04.356 --> 27:08.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
staying, so they can understand
what the current
state of affairs are and all the
issues they

27:08.360 --> 27:10.028 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
are going to inherit tomorrow.

27:10.128 --> 27:12.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And we should
say, General
Flynn, of course, is the
incoming national

27:12.464 --> 27:14.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
security adviser to the
president.

27:14.566 --> 27:15.467 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
K.T.

27:15.567 --> 27:17.402 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
McFarland is his deputy.

27:17.503 --> 27:22.074 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mark Landler, give us a picture
of the National
Security Council staff.

27:22.174 --> 27:27.412 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How many of those positions are
going to be
holdovers, if any, and how many
are going

27:27.513 --> 27:29.715 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to be empty when the Trump team
comes in?

27:29.815 --> 27:35.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK LANDLER: Well, Roger knows
more about
this than I do, but at the level
of the professional

27:35.687 --> 27:39.591 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
staff, you have a lot of
directorates in the
NSC.

27:39.691 --> 27:44.530 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The senior directors, the people
that run
those departments, tend to be
political appointees.

27:44.630 --> 27:49.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And most, if not all of those
jobs will be
vacant and will be filled by the
incoming

27:49.768 --> 27:51.169 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
administration.

27:51.270 --> 27:54.573 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But below that, you have a cadre
of professionals
at the director level.

27:54.673 --> 27:59.878 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Most of these people are
seconded from other
agencies, say, from the Pentagon
or the State

27:59.978 --> 28:03.549 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Department, and are at the White
House for
a set period of time.

28:03.649 --> 28:08.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When the Obama administration
came in, they
basically held over people in
those positions,

28:08.820 --> 28:11.590 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
which provided the important
continuity.

28:11.690 --> 28:14.826 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Trump team has told me they
plan to do
the same thing.

28:14.927 --> 28:19.565 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So it is not as though General
Flynn will
come in and find an empty
building.

28:19.665 --> 28:21.166 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
He won't.

28:21.266 --> 28:25.804 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He will find dozens of very
well-briefed,
experienced senior-level people.

28:25.904 --> 28:30.876 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What he will have to do, though,
very quickly
is put in a layer of senior
directors.

28:30.976 --> 28:35.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, they say that they have
identified and
chosen many of these people, and
they just

28:35.147 --> 28:37.449 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
haven't publicly announced them
yet.

28:37.549 --> 28:43.322 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So that will all unfold
presumably in the
opening days after the president
is inaugurated.

28:43.422 --> 28:49.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, again, where they have lost
time is in
all of these people reading into
the reams

28:49.561 --> 28:55.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and reams of paper that lay out
the administration's
current policies, that lay out
the major flash

28:55.267 --> 28:57.636 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
points they're going to face
around the world.

28:57.736 --> 29:02.874 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's time that they could
well have
used starting as early as late
November and

29:02.975 --> 29:04.743 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
early December of last year.

29:04.843 --> 29:06.979 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Roger
Cressey, if you're
part of this incoming Trump
team, what are

29:07.079 --> 29:08.947 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you worried that you may not
know?

29:09.047 --> 29:12.851 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROGER CRESSEY: Well, all special
assistants
to the president are typically
political appointees

29:12.951 --> 29:14.453 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the first year of the new
president.

29:14.553 --> 29:18.123 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, their job is to shape policy
for the new
president.

29:18.223 --> 29:22.160 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The career people that Mark
referred to are
there to provide continuity of
operations

29:22.260 --> 29:25.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to ensure that balls are not
dropped, but
they are not going to make any
new policy

29:25.464 --> 29:27.232 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
pronouncements.

