foreign policy,
it's national security policy,
do we read

30:10.108 --> 30:13.245 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
something into that by what's
happened right
now?

30:13.345 --> 30:19.084 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK LANDLER: Well, look, I
think it's fair
to say that this election
brought a very unexpected

30:19.184 --> 30:24.156 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
outcome, that the Trump people
were probably
starting off from a standing
start.

30:24.256 --> 30:26.725 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There was a lot of upheaval in
the early days.

30:26.825 --> 30:31.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You remember that the original
transition
team was led by Governor Chris
Christie, and

30:31.296 --> 30:34.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that team was purged almost
immediately after
the election.

30:34.332 --> 30:41.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I guess the one thing I would
watch for is
if this kind of upheaval,
improvisation, frequent

30:41.807 --> 30:47.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
shifts either in personnel or in
policy continue
to be a hallmark of the new
administration's

30:47.679 --> 30:49.448 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
style.

30:49.548 --> 30:53.218 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If they do, as some people think
they will,
we could be in for a bumpy ride
on national

30:53.318 --> 30:54.986 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
security.

30:55.087 --> 30:58.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it's also possible that once
they get
their team in place and they
settle down on

30:58.557 --> 31:04.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
their key priorities, that we
sort of return
to regular order, and things
begin unfolding.

31:04.996 --> 31:10.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I'm sure Roger will say,
every administration
faces a kind of a baptism by
fire, so I don't

31:10.168 --> 31:14.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
think it's fair to necessarily
assume that
these people are going to be off
the rails

31:14.172 --> 31:15.073 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
immediately.

31:15.173 --> 31:16.475 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Just 15 seconds.

31:16.575 --> 31:18.410 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What do you think in terms of
what this says
about the future?

31:18.510 --> 31:21.146 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROGER CRESSEY: The wheel of
government will
continue to work, even as these
people come

31:21.246 --> 31:25.484 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in and we wait for them, but the
issue is,
there's always one thing, as
Mark says, that

31:25.584 --> 31:27.486 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a new administration confronts.

31:27.586 --> 31:29.387 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the Bush administration, it
was terrorism.

31:29.488 --> 31:32.691 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For this administration, it's
going to be
cyber-security, not Russian
hacking.

31:32.791 --> 31:36.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's a symptom of the bigger
problem, but
the bigger issue of cyber, how
they deal with

31:36.995 --> 31:38.130 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
that.

31:38.230 --> 31:39.831 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, we may see something else
we're not anticipating.

31:39.931 --> 31:41.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
That's going to be their
challenge.

31:41.333 --> 31:42.434 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Roger Cressey,
Mark Landler,
thank you both.

31:42.534 --> 31:46.805 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARK LANDLER: Thank you so much.

31:46.905 --> 31:53.779 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ROGER CRESSEY: Thanks, Judy.

31:53.879 --> 32:01.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now our economics
correspondent
Paul Solman takes a look at what
has become

32:01.386 --> 32:07.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the new normal for many members
of the aging
middle class: financial
fragility.

32:07.425 --> 32:11.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's part of his weekly series,
Making Sense,
which airs Thursdays on the
"NewsHour."

32:11.296 --> 32:13.732 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ELIZABETH WHITE, Author,
"Fifty-Five, Unemployed
and Faking Normal": Everybody is
pretending.

32:13.832 --> 32:17.002 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And that's why you
call the book
"Faking Normal"?

32:17.102 --> 32:22.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH WHITE: Right, because
there's a
lot of pressure to seem like you
are doing

32:22.874 --> 32:24.609 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
well.

32:24.709 --> 32:29.881 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Elizabeth White is
not doing
terribly well, as she painfully
chronicles

32:29.981 --> 32:38.256 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
in the book she's just
self-published, "Fifty-Five
Unemployed and Faking Normal."

32:38.356 --> 32:41.893 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
White's been on the edge of the
financial
cliff for years, even though you
would never

32:41.993 --> 32:47.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
know it from how she looks or
the Washington,
D.C., townhouse she bought years
ago, one

32:47.766 --> 32:50.702 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
she couldn't even dream of
renting today.

32:50.802 --> 32:54.372 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But you haven't been in a
situation where
you literally couldn't afford
whatever it

32:54.472 --> 32:55.440 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is, the condo fee, or?

32:55.540 --> 32:57.542 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ELIZABETH WHITE: Oh, absolutely,
I have.

32:57.642 --> 33:03.648 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I right now have to park outside
because I'm
in arrears on the condo fee,
right now.

33:03.748 --> 33:08.653 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: And she's
refinanced to the hilt,
taken in a boarder.

33:08.753 --> 33:10.522 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Well, you haven't used food
stamps.

33:10.622 --> 33:11.723 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH WHITE: But I have.

33:11.823 --> 33:13.325 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I have had to.

33:13.425 --> 33:16.261 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: It's been quite a
comeuppance
for someone with her background.

33:16.361 --> 33:19.998 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
ELIZABETH WHITE: I have a
bachelor's from
Oberlin.

33:20.098 --> 33:24.569 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I have a master's in
international studies
from Johns Hopkins.

33:24.669 --> 33:30.208 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have a Harvard MBA, worked at
the World
Bank, came in through a program
where they

33:30.308 --> 33:32.444 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
recruited 5,000 people.

33:32.544 --> 33:35.046 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They took two Americans out of
that 25.

33:35.146 --> 33:36.982 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I was one of the Americans.

33:37.082 --> 33:40.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But, ultimately,
White decided
to leave the bank to start her
own business.

33:40.652 --> 33:44.122 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ELIZABETH WHITE: I had a chain
of stores,
of decorative home stores.

33:44.222 --> 33:45.123 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Really?

33:45.223 --> 33:46.591 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ELIZABETH WHITE: Yes.

33:46.691 --> 33:50.395 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I sold some of the things you
see here, African-inspired
products.

33:50.495 --> 33:56.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I realized that there was an
African-American
market that wanted things in
their home that

33:56.768 --> 33:58.837 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
reflected heritage and culture.

33:58.937 --> 34:02.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you wanted to give your
little girl a black
Raggedy Ann doll, you couldn't
easily find

34:02.274 --> 34:03.241 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it.

34:03.341 --> 34:05.110 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So I just curated that from all
over.

34:05.210 --> 34:11.416 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I then bet the ranch that I
could get
this going.

34:11.516 --> 34:18.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I took a lot of my -- not
all of it, but
I took a big chunk of my World
Bank money

34:18.356 --> 34:19.524 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to sort of fund this.

34:19.624 --> 34:20.558 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Retirement savings.

34:20.659 --> 34:22.394 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ELIZABETH WHITE: Savings.

34:22.494 --> 34:29.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it wasn't going -- it was
doing well,
but I couldn't see -- my vendors
of artisan

34:29.634 --> 34:34.406 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
producers were not going to be
able to blow
this out into a national chain,
were already

34:34.506 --> 34:36.541 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
struggling with volume.

34:36.641 --> 34:38.610 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Did you sell your
stores?

34:38.710 --> 34:39.611 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ELIZABETH WHITE: No.

34:39.711 --> 34:40.612 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Closed it in the end.

34:40.712 --> 34:42.681 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Just didn't -- didn't work.

34:42.781 --> 34:46.451 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: But steady
consulting work allowed
White to maintain an
upper-middle class lifestyle

34:46.551 --> 34:49.120 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for awhile, until the crash of
'08.

34:49.220 --> 34:54.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH WHITE: Within six
months, I went
from, you know, probably close
to 200?

34:54.259 --> 34:55.827 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Thousand dollars a
year.

34:55.927 --> 34:57.429 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH WHITE: Right, to zero.

34:57.529 --> 35:02.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And after that, the
jobs of the
past were nowhere to be found.

35:02.400 --> 35:10.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH WHITE: This is, to me,
where the
age discrimination piece
happens.

35:10.709 --> 35:18.950 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I find it much harder at this
phase of life
to get hired than I did earlier.

35:19.050 --> 35:21.119 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But you look so
young.

35:21.219 --> 35:24.522 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I'm not just saying that to,
you know,
flatter you or something.

35:24.622 --> 35:29.327 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, you surely can pass now
-- you're
62 or something?

35:29.427 --> 35:30.428 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ELIZABETH WHITE: Three.

35:30.528 --> 35:31.830 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Sixty-three.

35:31.930 --> 35:36.334 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you could pass for your 50s,
easily, mid-50s,
early 50s, right?

35:36.434 --> 35:40.105 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ELIZABETH WHITE: Early 50s is
not considered
young in the workplace.

35:40.205 --> 35:45.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: No, it's not, as we
learned in
an interview with economist
Teresa Ghilarducci,

35:45.677 --> 35:47.812 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
citing a study by the New York
Federal Reserve.

35:47.912 --> 35:52.584 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TERESA GHILARDUCCI, The New
School for Social
Research: From 45 to 55, wages
decrease by

35:52.684 --> 35:57.989 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
9 percent, from 55 to 65,
another 9 percent.

35:58.089 --> 36:03.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So this age earning profile,
where you kind
of peak and then it flattens out
and falls,

36:03.795 --> 36:07.599 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that age of peaking is a lot
younger than
we ever thought.

36:07.699 --> 36:12.971 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: And that
corresponds to age discrimination
as measured in economic
experiments by the

36:13.071 --> 36:17.776 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
likes of Joanna Lahey, who sent
fake resumes
to employers.

36:17.876 --> 36:23.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The red dots show where on the
resumes H.R.
managers looked, and for how
long.

36:24.049 --> 36:26.351 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And when does age discrimination
start?

36:26.451 --> 36:27.786 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOANNA LAHEY, The Bush School of
Government
and Public Service: Immediately.

36:27.886 --> 36:28.787 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It starts at age 35.

36:28.887 --> 36:29.788 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Really?

36:29.888 --> 36:30.789 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOANNA LAHEY: Yes.

36:30.889 --> 36:32.624 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's a pretty steady process.

36:32.724 --> 36:35.293 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And it's women more
than men?

36:35.393 --> 36:37.128 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOANNA LAHEY: It's definitely
women more than
men.

36:37.228 --> 36:42.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: No wonder career
coaches tell
you to wipe the dates off your
C.V., but,

36:42.500 --> 36:44.469 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
says White:

36:44.569 --> 36:48.973 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH WHITE: When they then
ask you to
fill out the application that's
all algorithm-driven,

36:49.074 --> 36:52.977 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you cannot leave off when you
graduated from
college.

36:53.078 --> 36:55.814 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And once you put that date in
there...

36:55.914 --> 36:56.815 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Then it's...

36:56.915 --> 36:58.349 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH WHITE: They know.

36:58.450 --> 37:02.387 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, as you get older, your
network also is
not what it used to be.

37:02.487 --> 37:03.755 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Because they're
losing their
jobs?

37:03.855 --> 37:05.256 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ELIZABETH WHITE: They're losing
their jobs.

37:05.356 --> 37:06.958 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They are retiring.

37:07.058 --> 37:08.793 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They're not hearing about
things.

37:08.893 --> 37:10.395 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They're winding down.

37:10.495 --> 37:12.030 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
People have died.

37:12.130 --> 37:15.767 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So, White has been
scraping by
with scattered freelance gigs.

37:15.867 --> 37:22.807 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH WHITE: It's sort of
bits and pieces
that allow me to cobble together
income.

37:22.907 --> 37:27.078 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But nowhere near
the income of
the past?

37:27.178 --> 37:28.646 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ELIZABETH WHITE: No, no.

37:28.746 --> 37:30.148 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Not even close.

37:30.248 --> 37:31.449 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ELIZABETH WHITE: No.

37:31.549 --> 37:34.119 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, again, I have years of,
you know,
under $30,000.

37:34.219 --> 37:39.524 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Help has come from
unexpected
sources, like neighborhood free
spirit Elijah,

37:39.624 --> 37:41.392 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a clothing minimalist.

37:41.493 --> 37:48.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH WHITE: I was getting
on the far
side of where my mortgage
company was getting,

37:48.933 --> 37:50.702 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
like, serious with me.

37:50.802 --> 37:52.070 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Because you were
behind in your
payments.

37:52.170 --> 37:53.071 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ELIZABETH WHITE: Behind.

37:53.171 --> 37:54.472 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He just said, Lizzy, I will do
it.

37:54.572 --> 37:56.007 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I can do it.

37:56.107 --> 37:58.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But I will do it,
meaning, I
will make up the difference.

37:58.543 --> 37:59.711 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ELIZABETH WHITE: Yes, I will do
it.

37:59.811 --> 38:02.313 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: I will pay -- he
will pay your
mortgage?

38:02.413 --> 38:03.615 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ELIZABETH WHITE: Right.

38:03.715 --> 38:06.050 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, this is my Elijah (ph).

38:06.151 --> 38:07.685 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's my Elijah, yes.

