and promoting them.

47:02.620 --> 47:05.256 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But it's such a beautiful form
to me.

47:05.356 --> 47:12.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I know that I'm not able to make
someone else's
film for them in, say, a studio
setting.

47:12.463 --> 47:19.236 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I can't have other people's
input who are
thinking about the commercial
viability of

47:19.336 --> 47:23.974 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the film affecting how the film
is made or
what goes into it.

47:24.075 --> 47:29.847 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I would end up in jail, having
kneecapped
some executive who previously
ran an underwear

47:29.947 --> 47:30.848 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
factory.

47:30.948 --> 47:32.850 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You know, I'm a filmmaker.

47:32.950 --> 47:34.919 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is what I'm learning to do.

47:35.019 --> 47:40.758 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In the film
"Paterson," Jarmusch
has also created an ode to an
earlier "Paterson,"

47:40.858 --> 47:46.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the epic poem written in the
1940s and '50s
by one of America's most
renowned poets, William

47:46.697 --> 47:47.832 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Carlos Williams.

47:47.932 --> 47:52.269 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Williams lived and worked as a
doctor in the
area.

47:52.369 --> 47:57.508 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the poem's preface, Williams
writes: "To
make a start out of particulars
and make them

47:57.608 --> 47:58.943 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
general."

47:59.043 --> 48:03.147 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The bus driver in the film
"Paterson" is no
William Carlos Williams.

48:03.247 --> 48:05.983 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's never published a thing and
is unlikely
to.

48:06.083 --> 48:07.785 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But he'd understand the
sentiment.

48:07.885 --> 48:11.589 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ADAM DRIVER: I'm working on a
poem for you.

48:11.689 --> 48:15.292 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ACTRESS: A love poem?

48:15.392 --> 48:16.327 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
ADAM DRIVER: Yes.

48:16.427 --> 48:19.096 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I guess, if it's for you, it's a
love poem.

48:19.196 --> 48:23.134 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And Jarmusch
picked up on the
notion of taking the particulars
of everyday

48:23.234 --> 48:27.238 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
life, looking at them, listening
to them and
making art from them.

48:27.338 --> 48:33.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JIM JARMUSCH: Because he's a bus
driver, and
we have images flowing past him,
both visually

48:34.044 --> 48:41.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and things he overhears, he kind
of drifts
through his job, which is very
-- it's a routine,

48:41.152 --> 48:42.052 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
right?

48:42.153 --> 48:44.522 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's all very set for him.

48:44.622 --> 48:47.691 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And this allows him to just take
things in.

48:47.792 --> 48:53.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that's what poets -- in
this case,
he's a poet -- all people who
create things,

48:54.098 --> 48:55.699 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
this is what they do.

48:55.800 --> 48:58.169 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have to get input from
something.

48:58.269 --> 49:02.807 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The stuff of life
becomes the
details of poetry.

49:02.907 --> 49:04.842 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
RON PADGETT: I hope so.

49:04.942 --> 49:06.777 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I can't figure out where else to
get it.

49:06.877 --> 49:08.612 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

49:08.712 --> 49:11.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I asked Ron
Padgett, who's
taught writing to children,
college students

49:11.649 --> 49:14.919 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and adults, what people too
often don't get
about poetry.

49:15.019 --> 49:19.824 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RON PADGETT: They are given to
quote, I think,
wrong or misleading or narrow
idea of what

49:19.924 --> 49:22.459 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
poetry is or can be.

49:22.560 --> 49:26.864 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, secondly, they don't value
their own
imaginations.

49:26.964 --> 49:30.367 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They just suppress or don't want
to deal with
their imagination.

49:30.467 --> 49:35.773 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And yet it's so close to being a
poet in many
ways.

49:35.873 --> 49:40.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, if we can only bust through
those barriers
-- and maybe a film like
"Paterson" will help

49:40.544 --> 49:44.849 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
some people say, huh, maybe I
could write
something like this, too.

49:44.949 --> 49:49.086 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
