50:09.106 --> 50:15.045 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, author and futurist Amy
Webb offers
us a glimpse of things to come
in the world

50:15.145 --> 50:16.947 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
of tech.

50:17.047 --> 50:21.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Her latest book is "The Signals
Are Talking:
Why Today's Fringe Is Tomorrow's
Mainstream."

50:21.151 --> 50:22.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AMY WEBB, Author, "The Signals
Are Talking:
Why Today's Fringe Is Tomorrow's
Mainstream":

50:22.987 --> 50:25.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We don't stop to think about it,
but if you
really want to freak yourself
out, and you

50:25.155 --> 50:31.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
own a cell phone, go to Google
and look up
your personal information, every
single place

50:31.528 --> 50:34.231 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that you have been since you
have been online.

50:34.331 --> 50:38.102 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
While we don't think about those
digital bread
crumbs, there are lots of third
parties out

50:38.202 --> 50:41.705 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there that are happily scooping
them up and
doing something with that data.

50:41.805 --> 50:47.144 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you stop to think about it,
your phone
knows you better, has a more
intimate relationship

50:47.244 --> 50:51.015 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with you than whoever it is that
you're sleeping
with, than your loved one.

50:51.115 --> 50:52.249 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is for PBS, isn't it?

50:52.349 --> 50:53.484 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I can't say that.

50:53.584 --> 50:56.954 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
QUESTION: You can say that.

50:57.054 --> 51:02.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AMY WEBB: We are entering a
period in which
you can be expected to talk to
machines for

51:03.027 --> 51:04.128 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the rest of your life.

51:04.228 --> 51:07.064 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The thing that's coming is
artificial intelligence.

51:07.164 --> 51:09.967 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It won't just be you talking to
a machine.

51:10.067 --> 51:13.570 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
A lot of it's going to be
invisible, and it's
going to make our lives easier.

51:13.671 --> 51:19.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's going to allow scientists
to leapfrog
ahead in their research.

51:19.543 --> 51:23.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I do believe that, within my
lifetime,
life as we know it on this
planet is probably

51:23.147 --> 51:24.815 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
going to look a little bit
different than
it is today.

51:24.915 --> 51:29.887 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's some really interesting
bioinformation
tools that are coming to market.

51:29.987 --> 51:32.957 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, one big trend is, how can we
prevent against
hackers?

51:33.057 --> 51:38.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
No matter how hard we try to
tell people,
you have got to change your
passwords, most

51:38.829 --> 51:40.631 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
people don't change their
passwords.

51:40.731 --> 51:44.768 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
What if we no longer had
passwords, but instead
we are using our own biometric
information?

51:44.868 --> 51:47.638 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You're probably already doing
that if you
have a newer phone.

51:47.738 --> 51:50.307 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You're using your thumbprint as
a way to make
payments.

51:50.407 --> 51:54.411 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Some of the interesting things
on the horizon
are things like heat maps.

51:54.511 --> 51:59.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
All of the capillaries of your
face are in
very slightly different places,
which means

51:59.650 --> 52:04.388 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that your face sort of gives off
this unique
heat map.

52:04.488 --> 52:08.525 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that unique heat map is one
way that we
can authenticate you.

52:08.625 --> 52:13.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the challenges with
technology is that,
as it becomes more
sophisticated, it also

52:13.797 --> 52:15.499 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
becomes more hidden.

52:15.599 --> 52:18.335 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you look under the hood of a
modern car,
you see what looks like a flat
surface.

52:18.435 --> 52:23.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Not every person who drives a
car needs to
be Lewis Hamilton's F1 pit crew
boss, but

52:23.807 --> 52:28.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I do think it's dangerous for us
to continue
going forward without having
some of that

52:28.545 --> 52:30.381 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
lexicon.

52:30.481 --> 52:34.218 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have to be able to have
conversations with
each other and with the people
creating these

52:34.318 --> 52:38.522 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
devices, because, if we can't
have the conversations,
then we can't ask the questions.

52:38.622 --> 52:43.227 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And if we can't ask the
questions, the problem
is that, 10 years into the
future, we're going

52:43.327 --> 52:48.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to look back at this moment in
time and wish
that we had done things
differently.

